        <p> ___Twig_token_1___ Before it went to the K&ouml;nigstein fortress, which had already made us curious yesterday. So we made our way to the entrance to the fortress, which - how could it be otherwise - could be reached with a small climb. But the view from above compensated us for the effort. Really great! The view of the Elbe valley and the surrounding forests was simply breathtaking. And the fortress itself? A real splendor, well maintained and full of history. We spent the next five hours exploring the facility, losing ourselves in the old walls and enjoying the view. </p>
        <p> We actually wanted to take part in a workshop where you could produce herbal salt. Sounds exciting, isn't it? Unfortunately, the workshop was canceled at short notice and replaced by a leather bag workshop. Stupid, that was probably nothing. </p>
        <p> After so much culture and history, it was time to take a break - and what fits better than a look at the Elbe? While we watched the steamer on the river, we realized: "We have to do that too!" We just wanted to look around on the water and to see the area from a different perspective. So we decided to stay a little in the region and to plan a little Elbe trip for tomorrow. </p>
        <p> But as it is so often in life: the plan was not so easy to implement. Our pipitank was full - and as chance wanted, there was no waste disposal station in the parking space. So it was said: to Pirna! </p>

